<TITLE> Adidas more optimistic for World Cup year after Q1 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 FRANKFURT, May 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) -- German sporting goods maker Adidas AG gave a more optimistic outlook for 2010 on Tuesday in anticipation of the soccer World Cup, which it sponsors, and further improvements at its Reebok brand. "With the Reebok turnaround gathering pace and the FIFA World Cup kicking off in a few weeks, we have a lot of reasons to be optimistic," Chief Executive Herbert Hainer said. The world's No 2 behind US bellwether Nike Inc now expects full-year sales to rise by a mid-single digit percentage range and sees its gross margin at 46.5 to 47.5 percent, it said. Adidas had already surprised markets last month by raising its 2010 net profit outlook and reporting better-than-expected first-quarter results ahead of schedule. Local rival Puma followed suit days later, also taking heart from strong quarterly results ahead of the soccer World Cup, due to kick off on June 11. The tournament, of which Adidas is key sponsor, already boosted the company's first-quarter sales, rising 4 percent to 2.67 billion euros ($3.56 billion), while its smaller rival Puma reported a drop in revenue for the same period. "We had a great start to the year, achieving record first-quarter sales driven by growth in all segments," CEO Hainer said, pointing to record football sales and a strong performance for Adidas and Reebok in North America. Adidas leads the pack in soccer. For the World Cup, it provides the official match balls, dresses the tournament's officials, such as referees, and equips 12 teams, including Germany, host nation South Africa and European champion Spain. Nike sponsors 10 teams and Puma seven. Adidas shares were indicated 0.3 percent lower, according to premarket data from brokers by 0623 GMT. Adidas shares trade at 17.4 times 12-month forward earnings, in line with Nike, which trades at a multiple of 17.6, according to Thomson Reuters StarMine, which weights analyst expectations according to their track record. Puma trades with 15.4, at a discou